<bibRefCitation id="336E4B25FFE54168CB6CEE47FE1F2720" author="Glenn, G. S. Jr." box="[298,429,1835,1861]" pageId="19" pageNumber="470" pagination="67 - 102" refId="ref16270" refString="Glenn, G. S. Jr. (1991) A systematic revision of Enyaliopsis Karsch 1887 (Orthoptera: Tettigoniidae, Hetrodinae). Transactions of the American Entomological Society, 117, 67 - 102. http: // www. jstor. org / stable / 25078540" type="journal article" year="1991">Glenn 1991</bibRefCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="574036D4FFE54168CA81EE22FB7527E8" blockId="19.[151,1436,1834,1933]" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFE54168CA81EE22FED0270D" bold="true" box="[199,354,1870,1896]" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">Bioacoustics.</emphasis>
Judging from the figure in 
<bibRefCitation id="336E4B25FFE54168C8D7EE23FC9B270C" author="Glenn, G. S. Jr." box="[657,809,1871,1897]" pageId="19" pageNumber="470" pagination="67 - 102" refId="ref16270" refString="Glenn, G. S. Jr. (1991) A systematic revision of Enyaliopsis Karsch 1887 (Orthoptera: Tettigoniidae, Hetrodinae). Transactions of the American Entomological Society, 117, 67 - 102. http: // www. jstor. org / stable / 25078540" type="journal article" year="1991">Glenn (1991)</bibRefCitation>
, the calling song of this species seems to have an unusually low SRR (9 Hz) with bipartite syllables and is possibly organized in echemes (see 
<tableCitation id="1A7D036FFFE54168CE23EE1FFB0827E8" box="[1125,1210,1907,1933]" captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,236,476,501]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="TABLE 2. Song characteristics of Hetrodini species (for song type see Fig. 5 and text)" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/0380665CFFF1417CCAD1E8B0FBBD2190" pageId="19" pageNumber="470" tableUuid="0380665CFFF1417CCAD1E8B0FBBD2190">Table 2</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
